<article>
    <h1>Net&#xAD;flix roar&#xAD;ing in a pan&#xAD;demic</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201227/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-27"><time>2020-12-27</time></a>
        - <span>FEATURES</span>
        - <span role="byline">John Lui</span>
    </section>

    <p>NET­FLIX</p>
    <p>Con­tent stream­ing ser­vice</p>
    <p>The year be­gan with bad news: A Net­flix sub­scrip­tion fee hike that took ef­fect for Sin­ga­pore sub­scribers in Jan­uary. But their un­hap­pi­ness must have been tem­pered some­what by the hit con­tent the stream­ing ser­vice re­leased.</p>
    <p>The drama se­ries The Queen’s Gam­bit, the Korean ro­man­tic drama se­ries It’s Okay To Not Be Okay and the erotic film 365 Days made clear­ing leave at home more bear­able.</p>
    <p>Ac­cord­ing to a study from con­sul­tancy PwC, a tip­ping point was reached in Sin­ga­pore this year: It es­ti­mated that more dol­lars will be spent on stream­ing video-on­de­mand, from providers like Net­flix, Ama­zon Prime Video, Viu, HBO Go and Ap­ple TV +, than in cin­e­mas.</p>
    <p>And next year, the spend­ing – through sub­scrip­tions and other fees – will beat that of spend­ing on tra­di­tional tele­vi­sion, such as ca­ble TV sub­scrip­tions.</p>
    <p>Lo­cal cin­e­mas have re­acted.</p>
    <p>Hit on two sides by the global cord-cut­ting trends as well as the pan­demic that has left cin­ema seats empty, Sin­ga­pore’s largest and third-largest cin­ema chains re­cently pro­posed a merger in the hopes of rais­ing in­vest­ment and cut­ting costs.</p>
    <p>The Cathay-Golden Vil­lage plan might have been pro­voked by the pan­demic-trig­gered drop in foot­fall, but an­other fac­tor must have been the news from the United States.</p>
    <p>Two Hol­ly­wood gi­ants, Dis­ney and Warn­erMe­dia (which owns the Warner Bros stu­dio and the HBO chan­nels), re­alised that phys­i­cal venues ex­posed them to too much risk from dis­as­ters. Both re­cently an­nounced plans to screen films on their own stream­ing ser­vices – Dis­ney+ and HBO Max – at the same time or soon af­ter open­ing them in cin­e­mas.</p>
    <p>So Net­flix de­serves pos­si­bly the top spot in the Power List this year be­cause it was a pi­o­neer in stream­ing in Sin­ga­pore and also launched the most talked-about con­tent.</p>
    <p>But next year, when Dis­ney+ launches here and should HBO Max also come, Net­flix’s spot – and peo­ple’s wal­lets – could be at risk.</p>
    <p>Watch this space.</p>

